Kubernetes Monitoring (10:25 - 11:19)
Kubernetes monitoring is the practice of continuously collecting, analyzing, and alerting on performance data across a cluster to ensure
high availability, resource optimization, and rapid troubleshooting. Unlike traditional infrastructure monitoring which tracks static
virtual machines, monitoring Kubernetes requires managing ephemeral, highly distributed, and short-lived containers that spin up and down
dynamically.

A comprehensive strategy targets four distinct layers of the cluster architecture:

Control Plane: Evaluates the core components like the kube-apiserver latency, kube-scheduler queue lengths, and etcd health.
Worker Nodes: Tracks bare-metal or VM-level health metrics including overall CPU saturation, memory exhaustion, local disk space, and
network throughput.
Pods and Containers: Observes specific runtime metrics like container throttling, crash loops, and restart counts.
Applications: Captures business-level logic, request latency, and HTTP error rates directly inside the workloads.

Core Telemetry Signals (The Pillars)
To attain true visibility, clusters rely on four primary observability data types:

Metrics: Numeric time-series values that track usage patterns over time (e.g., CPU/memory utilization against configured requests and
limits).
Logs: Detailed text streams generated by system components (like kubelet) and application code to trace why failures happen.
Traces: Lifecycle records that track the continuous path of a single end-user request across multiple microservices.
Events: Real-time Kubernetes API data points recording cluster-state changes, such as scheduling failures, node reboots, or image pull
errors.

Critical Metrics to Watch
CPU and Memory Saturation: Track actual usage versus configured container limits and requests to optimize your cloud spend.
Pod Restart Count: Spikes indicate underlying issues like Out-Of-Memory (OOM) kills or unhandled code exceptions.
Pending Pods: The number of workloads stuck waiting for the scheduler due to insufficient node capacity.
API Server Request Latency: High latency slows down all communication inside the control plane and degrades overall automation performance.

Popular Monitoring Solutions
Tools are typically split between open-source stacks and managed cloud platforms:

Prometheus & Grafana: The standard industry stack. Prometheus scrapes metrics from target endpoints, while Grafana surfaces visual 
dashboards. Teams often deploy them quickly using the kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart.
Kube-State-Metrics: A lightweight agent that listens to the Kubernetes API server and generates metrics regarding the health of objects
like deployments, pods, and jobs.
Enterprise Platforms: Managed solutions such as ⁠Grafana Cloud, Datadog, New Relic, and Dynatrace offer unified observability out-of-the-box
with automated AI-assisted root cause analysis

